weston.ini(5)                 File Formats Manual                weston.ini(5)

NNAAMMEE
       weston.ini - configuration file for WWeessttoonn - the reference Wayland com‐
       positor

IINNTTRROODDUUCCTTIIOONN
       WWeessttoonn obtains configuration from its command line parameters  and  the
       configuration file described here.

DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
       WWeessttoonn  uses a configuration file called _w_e_s_t_o_n_._i_n_i for its setup.  The
       _w_e_s_t_o_n_._i_n_i configuration file is searched for in one of  the  following
       places when the server is started:

           $$XXDDGG__CCOONNFFIIGG__HHOOMMEE//wweessttoonn..iinnii   (if $XDG_CONFIG_HOME is set)
           $$HHOOMMEE//..ccoonnffiigg//wweessttoonn..iinnii      (if $HOME is set)
           wweessttoonn//wweessttoonn..iinnii iinn eeaacchh
               $$XXDDGG__CCOONNFFIIGG__DDIIRR           (if $XDG_CONFIG_DIRS is set)
           //eettcc//xxddgg//wweessttoonn//wweessttoonn..iinnii    (if $XDG_CONFIG_DIRS is not set)
           <<ccuurrrreenntt ddiirr>>//wweessttoonn..iinnii      (if no variables were set)

       where  environment  variable  $$HHOOMMEE  is  the user's home directory, and
       $$XXDDGG__CCOONNFFIIGG__HHOOMMEE is the  user  specific  configuration  directory,  and
       $$XXDDGG__CCOONNFFIIGG__DDIIRRSS  is a colon ''::'' delimited listed of configuration base
       directories, such as //eettcc//xxddgg--ffoooo:://eettcc//xxddgg.

       The _w_e_s_t_o_n_._i_n_i file is composed of a number of sections  which  may  be
       present  in  any order, or omitted to use default configuration values.
       Each section has the form:

           [[_S_e_c_t_i_o_n_H_e_a_d_e_r]]
           Key1=Value1
           Key2=Value2
               ...

       The spaces are significant.  Comment lines are ignored:

           _#_c_o_m_m_e_n_t

       The section headers are:

           ccoorree           The core modules and options
           lliibbiinnppuutt       Input device configuration
           sshheellll          Desktop customization
           llaauunncchheerr       Add launcher to the panel
           oouuttppuutt         Output configuration
           iinnppuutt--mmeetthhoodd   Onscreen keyboard input
           kkeeyybbooaarrdd       Keyboard layouts
           tteerrmmiinnaall       Terminal application options
           xxwwaayyllaanndd       XWayland options
           ssccrreeeenn--sshhaarree   Screen sharing options

       Possible value types are string, signed and  unsigned  32-bit  integer,
       and  boolean.  Strings  must  not  be quoted, do not support any escape
       sequences, and run till the end of the line. Integers can be  given  in
       decimal  (e.g.  123),  octal  (e.g.  0173), and hexadecimal (e.g. 0x7b)
       form. Boolean values can be only 'true' or 'false'.

CCOORREE SSEECCTTIIOONN
       The ccoorree section is used to select the startup compositor  modules  and
       general options.

       sshheellll==_d_e_s_k_t_o_p_-_s_h_e_l_l_._s_o
              specifies  a  shell  to  load (string). This can be used to load
              your own implemented shell or one with Weston as default. Avail‐
              able shells in the _/_u_s_r_/_l_i_b_/_w_e_s_t_o_n directory are:

                 ddeesskkttoopp--sshheellll..ssoo

       xxwwaayyllaanndd==_t_r_u_e
              ask Weston to load the XWayland module (boolean).

       mmoodduulleess==_c_m_s_-_c_o_l_o_r_d_._s_o_,_s_c_r_e_e_n_-_s_h_a_r_e_._s_o
              specifies the modules to load (string). Available modules in the
              _/_u_s_r_/_l_i_b_/_w_e_s_t_o_n directory are:

                 ccmmss--ccoolloorrdd..ssoo
                 ssccrreeeenn--sshhaarree..ssoo

       bbaacckkeenndd==_h_e_a_d_l_e_s_s_-_b_a_c_k_e_n_d_._s_o
              overrides defaults backend. Available  backend  modules  in  the
              _/_u_s_r_/_l_i_b_/_w_e_s_t_o_n directory are:

                 ddrrmm--bbaacckkeenndd..ssoo
                 ffbbddeevv--bbaacckkeenndd..ssoo
                 hheeaaddlleessss--bbaacckkeenndd..ssoo
                 rrddpp--bbaacckkeenndd..ssoo
                 wwaayyllaanndd--bbaacckkeenndd..ssoo
                 xx1111--bbaacckkeenndd..ssoo

       rreeppaaiinntt--wwiinnddooww==_N
              Set  the  approximate  length of the repaint window in millisec‐
              onds. The repaint window is used to control and reduce the  out‐
              put latency for clients. If the window is longer than the output
              refresh period, the repaint will be done  immediately  when  the
              previous  repaint  finishes,  not  processing client requests in
              between. If the repaint window is too short, the compositor  may
              miss  the  target vertical blank, increasing output latency. The
              default value is 7 milliseconds. The allowed range is  from  -10
              to 1000 milliseconds. Using a negative value will force the com‐
              positor to always miss the target vblank.

       ggbbmm--ffoorrmmaatt==_f_o_r_m_a_t
              sets the GBM format used for the framebuffer for the  GBM  back‐
              end. Can be xxrrggbb88888888,, xxrrggbb22110011001100,, rrggbb556655..  By default, xrgb8888
              is used.

       iiddllee--ttiimmee==_s_e_c_o_n_d_s
              sets Weston's idle timeout in seconds. This idle timeout is  the
              time after which Weston will enter an "inactive" mode and screen
              will fade to black. A value of 0 disables the timeout.

              _I_m_p_o_r_t_a_n_t : This option may also be set via Weston's  '-i'  com‐
              mand  line option and will take precedence over the current .ini
              option. This means that if  both  weston.ini  and  command  line
              define this idle-timeout time, the one specified in the command-
              line will be used. On the other hand, if none of these sets  the
              value, default idle timeout will be set to 300 seconds.

       rreeqquuiirree--iinnppuutt==_t_r_u_e
              require an input device for launch

       ppaaggeefflliipp--ttiimmeeoouutt==_m_i_l_l_i_s_e_c_o_n_d_s
              sets  Weston's  pageflip  timeout  in milliseconds.  This sets a
              timer to exit gracefully with a log message and an exit code  of
              1  in  case  the  DRM driver is non-responsive.  Setting it to 0
              disables this feature.

       wwaaiitt--ffoorr--ddeebbuuggggeerr==_t_r_u_e
              Raises SIGSTOP before initializing the compositor.  This  allows
              the  user  to  attach  with a debugger and continue execution by
              sending SIGCONT. This is useful for debugging a crash on  start-
              up  when it would be inconvenient to launch weston directly from
              a debugger. Boolean, defaults to ffaallssee.  There is also a command
              line option to do the same.

LLIIBBIINNPPUUTT SSEECCTTIIOONN
       The  lliibbiinnppuutt section is used to configure input devices when using the
       libinput input device backend.

       Available configuration are:

       eennaabbllee__ttaapp==_t_r_u_e
              enables tap to click on touchpad devices

SSHHEELLLL SSEECCTTIIOONN
       The sshheellll section is used to customize the compositor.  Some  keys  may
       not be handled by different shell plugins.

       The entries that can appear in this section are:

       cclliieenntt==_f_i_l_e
              sets  the  path  for  the  shell client to run. If not specified
              _w_e_s_t_o_n_-_d_e_s_k_t_o_p_-_s_h_e_l_l is launched (string).

       bbaacckkggrroouunndd--iimmaaggee==_f_i_l_e
              sets the path for the background image file (string).

       bbaacckkggrroouunndd--ttyyppee==_t_i_l_e
              determines how the background image is drawn  (string).  Can  be
              ssccaallee,  ssccaallee--ccrroopp or ttiillee (default).  Scale means scaled to fit
              the output precisely, not preserving aspect  ratio.   Scale-crop
              preserves  aspect  ratio,  scales  the background image just big
              enough to cover the output, and centers it. The  image  ends  up
              cropped  from  left  and right, or top and bottom, if the aspect
              ratio does not match the output.  Tile  repeats  the  background
              image to fill the output.

       bbaacckkggrroouunndd--ccoolloorr==_0_x_A_A_R_R_G_G_B_B
              sets  the  color of the background (unsigned integer). The hexa‐
              decimal digit pairs are in order alpha, red, green, and blue.

       cclloocckk--ffoorrmmaatt==_f_o_r_m_a_t
              sets the panel clock format (string). Can be nnoonnee, mmiinnuutteess, sseecc‐‐
              oonnddss.  By default, minutes format is used.

       ppaanneell--ccoolloorr==_0_x_A_A_R_R_G_G_B_B
              sets  the color of the panel (unsigned integer). The hexadecimal
              digit pairs are in order transparency,  red,  green,  and  blue.
              Examples:

                 00xxffffffff00000000    Red
                 00xxffff0000ffff0000    Green
                 00xxffff00000000ffff    Blue
                 00xx0000ffffffffffff    Fully transparent

       ppaanneell--ppoossiittiioonn==_t_o_p
              sets  the  position  of  the panel (string). Can be ttoopp,, bboottttoomm,,
              lleefftt,, rriigghhtt,, nnoonnee..

       lloocckkiinngg==_t_r_u_e
              enables screen locking (boolean).

       aanniimmaattiioonn==_z_o_o_m
              sets the effect used for opening new windows  (string).  Can  be
              zzoooomm,, ffaaddee,, nnoonnee..  By default, no animation is used.

       cclloossee--aanniimmaattiioonn==_f_a_d_e
              sets the effect used when closing windows (string). Can be ffaaddee,,
              nnoonnee..  By default, the fade animation is used.

       ssttaarrttuupp--aanniimmaattiioonn==_f_a_d_e
              sets the effect used for opening new windows  (string).  Can  be
              ffaaddee,, nnoonnee..  By default, the fade animation is used.

       ffooccuuss--aanniimmaattiioonn==_d_i_m_-_l_a_y_e_r
              sets the effect used with the focused and unfocused windows. Can
              be ddiimm--llaayyeerr,, nnoonnee..  By default, no animation is used.

       aallllooww--zzaapp==_t_r_u_e
              whether the shell should quit when  the  Ctrl-Alt-Backspace  key
              combination is pressed

       bbiinnddiinngg--mmooddiiffiieerr==_c_t_r_l
              sets the modifier key used for common bindings (string), such as
              moving surfaces, resizing, rotating, switching, closing and set‐
              ting the transparency for windows, controlling the backlight and
              zooming the desktop. Possible values:  none,  ctrl,  alt,  super
              (default)

       nnuumm--wwoorrkkssppaacceess==_6
              defines  the  number  of workspaces (unsigned integer). The user
              can switch workspaces by using the binding+F1, F2 keys. If  this
              key is not set, fall back to one workspace.

       ccuurrssoorr--tthheemmee==_t_h_e_m_e
              sets the cursor theme (string).

       ccuurrssoorr--ssiizzee==_2_4
              sets the cursor size (unsigned integer).

       lloocckkssccrreeeenn--iiccoonn==_p_a_t_h
              sets  the path to lock screen icon image (string). (tablet shell
              only)

       lloocckkssccrreeeenn==_p_a_t_h
              sets the path to lock screen background image (string).  (tablet
              shell only)

       hhoommeessccrreeeenn==_p_a_t_h
              sets  the path to home screen background image (string). (tablet
              shell only)

LLAAUUNNCCHHEERR SSEECCTTIIOONN
       There can be multiple launcher sections, one for each launcher.

       iiccoonn==_i_c_o_n
              sets the path to icon image (string). Svg images  are  not  cur‐
              rently supported.

       ppaatthh==_p_r_o_g_r_a_m
              sets  the  path  to  the program that is run by clicking on this
              launcher (string).  It is possible to pass arguments  and  envi‐
              ronment variables to the program. For example:

                  path=GDK_BACKEND=wayland gnome-terminal --full-screen

OOUUTTPPUUTT SSEECCTTIIOONN
       There  can  be multiple output sections, each corresponding to one out‐
       put. It is currently only recognized by the drm and x11 backends.

       nnaammee==_n_a_m_e
              sets a name for the output (string). The backend uses  the  name
              to identify the output. All X11 output names start with a letter
              X.  All Wayland output names start with  the  letters  WL.   The
              available output names for DRM backend are listed in the wweessttoonn--
              llaauunncchh((11)) output.  Examples of usage:

                 LLVVDDSS11    DRM backend, Laptop internal panel no.1
                 VVGGAA11     DRM backend, VGA connector no.1
                 XX11       X11 backend, X window no.1
                 WWLL11      Wayland backend, Wayland window no.1

              See wweessttoonn--ddrrmm((77)) for more details.

       mmooddee==_m_o_d_e
              sets the output mode (string). The  mode  parameter  is  handled
              differently  depending  on  the  backend. On the X11 backend, it
              just sets the WIDTHxHEIGHT of the weston window.  The DRM  back‐
              end accepts different modes:

                 WWIIDDTTHHxxHHEEIIGGHHTT    Resolution size width and height in pixels
                 pprreeffeerrrreedd       Uses the preferred mode
                 ccuurrrreenntt         Uses the current crt controller mode
                 ooffff             Disables the output

              Optionally, a user may specify a modeline, such as:

                  173.00  1920 2048 2248 2576  1080 1083 1088 1120 -hsync +vsync

              It  consists  of the refresh rate in Hz, horizontal and vertical
              resolution, options for horizontal and vertical synchronisation.
              The program ccvvtt((11)) can provide suitable modeline string.

       ttrraannssffoorrmm==_n_o_r_m_a_l
              The transformation applied to screen output (string). The trans‐
              form key can be one of the following 8 strings:

                 nnoorrmmaall        Normal output.
                 9900            90 degrees clockwise.
                 118800           Upside down.
                 227700           90 degrees counter clockwise.
                 fflliippppeedd       Horizontally flipped
                 fflliippppeedd--9900    Flipped and 90 degrees clockwise
                 fflliippppeedd--118800   Flipped upside down
                 fflliippppeedd--227700   Flipped and 90 degrees counter clockwise

       ssccaallee==_f_a_c_t_o_r
              The scaling multiplier applied to the entire output, in  support
              of  high resolution ("HiDPI" or "retina") displays, that roughly
              corresponds to the pixel ratio of the display's physical resolu‐
              tion  to  the logical resolution.  Applications that do not sup‐
              port high resolution displays typically appear tiny and  unread‐
              able.  Weston will scale the output of such applications by this
              multiplier, to make them readable. Applications that do  support
              their  own output scaling can draw their content in high resolu‐
              tion, in which case they avoid compositor scaling.  Weston  will
              not  scale  the  output  of  such applications, and they are not
              affected by this multiplier.

              An integer, 1 by default, typically configured as  2  or  higher
              when needed, denoting the scaling multiplier for the output.

       sseeaatt==_n_a_m_e
              The logical seat name that that this output should be associated
              with. If this is set then the seat's input will be  confined  to
              the  output that has the seat set on it. The expectation is that
              this functionality will be used  in  a  multiheaded  environment
              with  a single compositor for multiple output and input configu‐
              rations. The default seat is called "default" and will always be
              present. This seat can be constrained like any other.

IINNPPUUTT--MMEETTHHOODD SSEECCTTIIOONN
       ppaatthh==_/_u_s_r_/_l_i_b_e_x_e_c_/_w_e_s_t_o_n_-_k_e_y_b_o_a_r_d
              sets the path of the on screen keyboard input method (string).

KKEEYYBBOOAARRDD SSEECCTTIIOONN
       This section contains the following keys:

       kkeeyymmaapp__rruulleess==_e_v_d_e_v
              sets  the  keymap  rules  file  (string). Used to map layout and
              model to input device.

       kkeeyymmaapp__mmooddeell==_p_c_1_0_5
              sets the keymap model (string). See the Models section in  xxkkeeyy‐‐
              bbooaarrdd--ccoonnffiigg((77))..

       kkeeyymmaapp__llaayyoouutt==_u_s_,_d_e_,_g_b
              sets the comma separated list of keyboard layout codes (string).
              See the Layouts section in xxkkeeyybbooaarrdd--ccoonnffiigg((77))..

       kkeeyymmaapp__vvaarriiaanntt==_e_u_r_o_,_,_i_n_t_l
              sets the  comma  separated  list  of  keyboard  layout  variants
              (string).  The number of variants must be the same as the number
              of layouts above. See  the  Layouts  section  in  xxkkeeyybbooaarrdd--ccoonn‐‐
              ffiigg((77))..

       kkeeyymmaapp__ooppttiioonnss==_g_r_p_:_a_l_t___s_h_i_f_t___t_o_g_g_l_e_,_g_r_p___l_e_d_:_s_c_r_o_l_l
              sets  the  keymap  options  (string). See the Options section in
              xxkkeeyybbooaarrdd--ccoonnffiigg((77))..

       rreeppeeaatt--rraattee==_4_0
              sets the  rate  of  repeating  keys  in  characters  per  second
              (unsigned integer)

       rreeppeeaatt--ddeellaayy==_4_0_0
              sets  the  delay  in milliseconds since key down until repeating
              starts (unsigned integer)

       nnuummlloocckk--oonn==_f_a_l_s_e
              sets the default state of the numlock on weston startup for  the
              backends which support it.

       vvtt--sswwiittcchhiinngg==_t_r_u_e
              Whether  to  allow  the  use  of Ctrl+Alt+Fn key combinations to
              switch away from the compositor's virtual console.

TTEERRMMIINNAALL SSEECCTTIIOONN
       Contains settings for the weston  terminal  application  (weston-termi‐
       nal).  It  allows  to  customize the font and shell of the command line
       interface.

       ffoonntt==_D_e_j_a_V_u _S_a_n_s _M_o_n_o
              sets the font of the terminal (string). For a good experience it
              is  recommended  to use monospace fonts. In case the font is not
              found, the default one is used.

       ffoonntt--ssiizzee==_1_4
              sets the size of the terminal font (unsigned integer).

       tteerrmm==_x_t_e_r_m_-_2_5_6_c_o_l_o_r
              The terminal shell (string). Sets the $TERM variable.

XXWWAAYYLLAANNDD SSEECCTTIIOONN
       ppaatthh==_/_u_s_r_/_b_i_n_/_X_w_a_y_l_a_n_d
              sets the path to the xserver to run (string).

SSCCRREEEENN--SSHHAARREE SSEECCTTIIOONN
       ccoommmmaanndd==_/_u_s_r_/_b_i_n_/_w_e_s_t_o_n  _-_-_b_a_c_k_e_n_d_=_r_d_p_-_b_a_c_k_e_n_d_._s_o   _-_-_s_h_e_l_l_=_f_u_l_l_s_c_r_e_e_n_-
       _s_h_e_l_l_._s_o _-_-_n_o_-_c_l_i_e_n_t_s_-_r_e_s_i_z_e
              sets  the  command to start a fullscreen-shell server for screen
              sharing (string).

